VALUES
('bb013001-0000-4000-8000-000000000001', 'tirupati-darshan-tips-2025', 'Tirupati Darshan 2025: Complete Guide for First-Time Visitors',
 'Planning your first Tirupati Balaji darshan? Here''s everything you need to know — from VIP darshan booking to accommodation, dress code, prasadam, and how to avoid the common pitfalls.',
 '<h2>Getting There</h2><p>Tirupati is well connected by air, rail, and road. The nearest airport is Tirupati Airport (TIR), while Tirupati Railway Station receives trains from Chennai, Bangalore, and Hyderabad. From Tirupati town, take a TTD (Tirumala Tirupati Devasthanam) bus or taxi to Tirumala hills — the bus journey takes about 45 minutes on the ghat road.</p><h2>Types of Darshan</h2><p><strong>Sarva Darshan (Free):</strong> This is the general darshan queue which can take 8-20 hours depending on the day. Weekdays are less crowded than weekends and festival days.</p><p><strong>Special Entry Darshan (Rs. 300):</strong> Book online at tirupatibalaji.ap.gov.in at least 3 months in advance. This gives priority access and usually takes 2-4 hours.</p><p><strong>Arjitha Sevas:</strong> Special rituals like Suprabhatham, Thomala Seva, and Sahasra Deepalankara Seva can be booked for a more intimate spiritual experience.</p><h2>Dress Code</h2><p>Men must wear dhoti (lungi with upper cloth) or kurta-pyjama. Women should wear saree or salwar kameez with dupatta. Jeans, shirts, shorts, and sleeveless tops are NOT permitted. Traditional attire can be rented near the queue complex.</p><h2>What to Carry</h2><p>Carry only minimal belongings. Mobile phones are not allowed inside the main temple. Deposit your phone at the free cloakroom. Carry a copy of your booking confirmation if you have Special Entry Darshan.</p><h2>Laddu Prasadam</h2><p>The famous Tirupati laddu is available for purchase. Two laddus are free with each Sarva Darshan ticket. Additional laddus must be purchased in advance at designated counters.</p><h2>Best Time to Visit</h2><p>October to February is the best time to visit. Avoid Brahmotsavam festival (September) and weekends unless you have advance bookings, as queues can stretch to 24 hours.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2161449/pexels-photo-2161449.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Pilgrimage', ARRAY['Tirupati','Darshan Guide','South India','Temple Tour'], 'Ramesh Kumar', 8, true, '2025-01-15 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013002-0000-4000-8000-000000000002', 'char-dham-yatra-preparation-guide', 'Char Dham Yatra 2025: How to Prepare for the Ultimate Himalayan Pilgrimage',
 'The Char Dham Yatra is the most sacred pilgrimage in Hinduism. This comprehensive guide covers registration, fitness requirements, acclimatization, packing list, best routes, and everything you need to know before undertaking this life-changing journey.',
 '<h2>What is Char Dham?</h2><p>The Char Dham refers to the four sacred shrines in the Garhwal Himalayas of Uttarakhand — Yamunotri, Gangotri, Kedarnath, and Badrinath. Visiting all four is considered one of the most meritorious acts in Hinduism, believed to cleanse all sins and grant moksha.</p><h2>Registration & Permits</h2><p>Since 2021, all pilgrims must register online at registrationandtouristcare.uk.gov.in. This is mandatory and free. Registration helps the government manage crowd flow and provides emergency contact details.</p><h2>Best Time to Visit</h2><p>The Char Dham temples open in May (after Akshaya Tritiya) and close in November (Diwali period). June-August brings monsoon with risks of landslides. May, September, and October are the best months.</p><h2>Fitness Requirements</h2><p>Kedarnath requires a 16km trek at 3584m altitude. Yamunotri requires a 6km trek. You must be in reasonably good physical health. Consult your doctor if you have heart conditions, hypertension, or respiratory issues. Altitude sickness (AMS) is common above 3000m — symptoms include headache, nausea, and dizziness.</p><h2>Acclimatization Tips</h2><p>Spend at least one night at 1500m (Haridwar/Rishikesh) before ascending. Drink plenty of water (3-4 liters/day). Avoid alcohol. Walk slowly. If symptoms worsen, descend immediately. Carry Diamox (consult doctor) as preventive medication.</p><h2>Packing List</h2><p>Warm layers (temperatures drop below 0°C at Kedarnath), rain gear, trekking shoes, first aid kit, oxygen cylinder (for emergencies), glucose biscuits, ORS packets, sunscreen, and woolens. Keep luggage under 10kg for the trek portions.</p><h2>Sample Itinerary</h2><p>The ideal itinerary is 11-14 days starting and ending at Haridwar: Haridwar → Barkot → Yamunotri → Uttarkashi → Gangotri → Guptkashi → Kedarnath → Badrinath → Rishikesh → Haridwar.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2387871/pexels-photo-2387871.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Pilgrimage', ARRAY['Char Dham','Kedarnath','Badrinath','Himalayan Yatra','Preparation Guide'], 'Priya Sharma', 12, true, '2025-02-10 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013003-0000-4000-8000-000000000003', 'kerala-backwaters-houseboat-guide', 'Kerala Houseboat Experience: Everything You Need to Know',
 'A night aboard a traditional Kerala houseboat (kettuvallam) is one of India''s most magical travel experiences. Here''s your complete guide to choosing the right houseboat, the best routes, and making the most of your backwater journey.',
 '<h2>What is a Kettuvallam?</h2><p>Kettuvallam are traditional rice barges that were historically used to transport rice through Kerala''s extensive network of backwaters, rivers, and lakes. Today, these wooden boats are converted into floating hotels with bedrooms, a kitchen, and a viewing deck.</p><h2>Best Houseboat Routes</h2><p><strong>Alleppey (Alappuzha):</strong> The most popular starting point. Routes through Vembanad Lake, Kuttanad (the rice bowl of Kerala), and the village canals. Best for first-timers.</p><p><strong>Kumarakom:</strong> More secluded and scenic. On the eastern shores of Vembanad Lake with excellent bird watching opportunities.</p><p><strong>Kollam:</strong> Starting point for the famous Kollam-Alleppey day cruise (8 hours, KSRTC operated, budget option).</p><h2>Types of Houseboats</h2><p>Houseboats range from basic (1-2 bedrooms, fan, simple meals) to premium (AC bedrooms, sun deck, gourmet chef, TV). Prices range from Rs. 5,000 to Rs. 25,000+ per night for the whole boat.</p><h2>What to Expect</h2><p>The boat glides silently through narrow canals lined with coconut palms, past local village life, toddy shops, and churches. Fresh fish, prawns, and traditional Kerala meals are prepared on board. In the evening, the boat moors at a designated spot — you cannot cruise overnight due to regulations.</p><h2>Best Time to Visit</h2><p>October to March is ideal. Monsoon (June-August) is atmospheric but some routes are restricted. August brings the famous Nehru Trophy Boat Race at Alleppey.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2387416/pexels-photo-2387416.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Travel Guide', ARRAY['Kerala','Houseboat','Backwaters','Alleppey','Kumarakom'], 'Anita Nair', 9, true, '2025-02-20 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013004-0000-4000-8000-000000000004', 'rajasthan-camel-safari-jaisalmer', 'Jaisalmer Desert Safari: The Ultimate Guide to Camel Trekking in Rajasthan',
 'The Thar Desert of Jaisalmer is one of India''s most extraordinary experiences. This guide covers the best safari routes, what to expect on a camel trek, where to stay under the stars, and how to avoid tourist traps.',
 '<h2>Jaisalmer — The Golden City</h2><p>Jaisalmer is a fairy-tale city rising from the Thar Desert, its golden sandstone fort and havelis glowing amber at sunset. The Sam Sand Dunes, 42km from Jaisalmer, are the starting point for most desert safaris.</p><h2>Types of Safaris</h2><p><strong>Short Sunset Safaris (1-2 hours):</strong> Most popular. A camel ride to a dune top for sunset, followed by cultural performances and dinner at the camp. Perfect for budget travelers or those with limited time.</p><p><strong>Overnight Desert Camping:</strong> The real experience — trek for 2-3 hours by camel, camp under an ocean of stars with nothing but dunes around you. Bonfire, folk music, and a wake-up to the desert sunrise.</p><p><strong>Multi-Day Treks (3-7 days):</strong> For serious adventurers — traverse remote desert villages, ancient caravansaries, and reach the Thar''s heart. Increasingly popular with international travelers.</p><h2>What to Carry</h2><p>Sunscreen (SPF 50+), sunglasses, a light scarf to cover your head, comfortable cotton clothes, and a water bottle. Desert temperatures swing dramatically — scorching by day (40°C+ in summer), surprisingly cold at night.</p><h2>Best Time to Visit</h2><p>October to February is ideal. March to May is brutally hot (45°C+). June to September is monsoon. The Desert Festival (February) is a spectacular time with camel races, folk performances, and Mr. Desert competition.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/3573351/pexels-photo-3573351.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Travel Guide', ARRAY['Rajasthan','Jaisalmer','Desert Safari','Camel Trek','Sam Sand Dunes'], 'Vikram Singh', 7, true, '2025-03-05 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013005-0000-4000-8000-000000000005', 'bali-travel-guide-indians', 'Bali for Indian Travelers: Complete 2025 Guide',
 'Bali remains one of the most popular international destinations for Indian tourists. Here''s everything you need to know — visa, currency, cultural etiquette, best areas to stay, and the hidden gems beyond the tourist trail.',
 '<h2>Visa & Entry</h2><p>Indian passport holders get visa-free access to Bali (Indonesia) for 30 days since 2023. Alternatively, the e-VOA (Electronic Visa on Arrival) costs $35 and can be applied for online before travel. Check the latest regulations before your trip.</p><h2>Best Areas to Stay</h2><p><strong>Seminyak/Kuta:</strong> Best for beach lovers, nightlife, and shopping. Most hotels and villas are concentrated here.</p><p><strong>Ubud:</strong> The cultural heart — rice terraces, artisan workshops, yoga retreats, and temple ceremonies. Perfect for couples and spiritual seekers.</p><p><strong>Nusa Dua:</strong> Premium resort area with calm, protected beaches. Ideal for families.</p><p><strong>Canggu:</strong> Trendy surf town with excellent cafes, boutiques, and the digital nomad crowd.</p><h2>Food for Indian Travelers</h2><p>Finding vegetarian and Indian food in Bali is surprisingly easy. Ubud has excellent vegetarian cafes. Most hotels can arrange Indian meals. However, Bali is famous for its own cuisine — try Babi Guling (suckling pig), Nasi Goreng (fried rice), and Satay at local warungs.</p><h2>Currency & Costs</h2><p>The Indonesian Rupiah (IDR) is the currency. Rs. 1 = approximately 165 IDR. Bali is affordable — a decent restaurant meal costs 50,000-150,000 IDR (Rs. 300-900). Always carry cash as many local shops and warungs don''t accept cards.</p><h2>Cultural Etiquette</h2><p>Bali is a predominantly Hindu island — deeply religious and culturally rich. Cover your shoulders and knees before entering temples. Wear a sarong (provided at temple entrances). During cremation processions, step aside respectfully. Never point feet at sacred objects or sit higher than a priest during ceremonies.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2166553/pexels-photo-2166553.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Destination Guide', ARRAY['Bali','International Travel','Indonesia','Travel Tips'], 'Sneha Menon', 10, true, '2025-03-15 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013006-0000-4000-8000-000000000006', 'varanasi-ganga-aarti-experience', 'Varanasi Ganga Aarti: A Spiritual Encounter with India''s Soul',
 'The Ganga Aarti at Dashashwamedh Ghat in Varanasi is one of the most mesmerizing spiritual experiences in the world. This guide tells you exactly how to experience it at its finest — the best vantage points, timing, and the stories behind each ritual.',
 '<h2>The City That Never Sleeps</h2><p>Varanasi (Kashi, Benaras) is one of the world''s oldest continuously inhabited cities — over 3,000 years old. For Hindus, dying in Varanasi is considered the ultimate liberation (moksha), as Lord Shiva himself is said to whisper the Taraka mantra (liberation mantra) into the ears of the dying. The city breathes with an otherworldly energy.</p><h2>The Ganga Aarti Ceremony</h2><p>Every evening at sunset, seven priests perform the Ganga Aarti simultaneously at Dashashwamedh Ghat in a perfectly synchronized, hour-long ceremony. The priests carry large brass lamps with multiple wicks, incense, and conch shells. The chanting, bells, and the reflection of fire on the Ganges create an ethereal scene.</p><h2>Best Vantage Points</h2><p><strong>Boat on the River:</strong> The best experience. Book a boat for Rs. 200-500 per person, row out to mid-river, and watch the ceremony from the water. You can also float a diya (earthen lamp) as an offering.</p><p><strong>Ghat Steps:</strong> Arrive early (30-45 minutes before sunset) to get a good spot on the ghat steps. It gets very crowded, especially on weekends.</p><p><strong>Rooftop Cafes:</strong> Several cafes behind the ghat have rooftop seating with views over the ceremony.</p><h2>Morning Boat Ride</h2><p>The morning boat ride (5:30-7am) is equally magical. Watch the city wake up, witness the morning rituals at the ghats, see the smoky pyres at Manikarnika Ghat (the burning ghat), and observe pilgrims performing their ablutions as the sun rises over the Ganges.</p><h2>Practical Tips</h2><p>Hire only government-registered boats. Avoid touts. The morning ride (Rs. 150-300 per person for a shared boat) is the best value. Ask your hotel to arrange it the evening before.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/3581368/pexels-photo-3581368.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Pilgrimage', ARRAY['Varanasi','Ganga Aarti','Kashi','Spiritual Travel','North India'], 'Dr. Arun Mishra', 11, true, '2025-04-01 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013007-0000-4000-8000-000000000007', 'leh-ladakh-road-trip-guide', 'Leh Ladakh Road Trip: The Ultimate High-Altitude Adventure',
 'The Manali-Leh highway and Srinagar-Leh highway are among the most spectacular roads on earth. This guide covers route options, bike vs. car debate, acclimatization protocol, best campsites, and the stunning landscapes you''ll encounter.',
 '<h2>When to Go</h2><p>The Manali-Leh highway is open from June to October. The Srinagar-Leh highway opens in May and stays open slightly longer. Winter Chadar (frozen river) trek runs January-February — a completely different adventure.</p><h2>Route Options</h2><p><strong>Manali-Leh Highway (474km):</strong> The classic. Crosses 5 high mountain passes including Rohtang (3978m), Baralacha La (4890m), Nakee La (4739m), Lachulung La (5059m), and Tanglang La (5328m). Takes 2 days with one overnight at Sarchu or Pang.</p><p><strong>Srinagar-Leh Highway (434km):</strong> Softer entry point. Passes through Sonamarg, Zoji La, Kargil, Lamayuru. Also 2 days with night halt at Kargil.</p><h2>Acclimatization is Non-Negotiable</h2><p>Leh is at 3500m. Altitude sickness (AMS) is real and can be life-threatening if ignored. Spend your first two days in Leh resting — short walks only, no exertion, drink 4+ liters of water daily, avoid alcohol. Most itineraries suggest flying in and going to Pangong the very next day — DON''T do this.</p><h2>Bike vs. Car</h2><p>Bike (Royal Enfield Himalayan or 350): The romantic choice. Raw, immersive, and challenging. Requires mechanical knowledge and physical fitness.</p><p>Car (Innova, Bolero, or similar): Comfortable, practical for families, and allows you to see more in less time. SUVs are recommended as roads are rough.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1366957/pexels-photo-1366957.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Adventure', ARRAY['Leh Ladakh','Road Trip','Adventure','Himalayas','Motorcycle'], 'Karan Mehta', 13, true, '2025-04-10 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013008-0000-4000-8000-000000000008', 'andaman-scuba-diving-guide', 'Andaman Islands Scuba Diving: India''s Best Underwater Paradise',
 'The Andaman Islands boast some of India''s best diving sites with pristine coral reefs, manta rays, whale sharks, and visibility up to 30 meters. This guide covers dive sites, PADI courses, best time to dive, and tips for beginners.',
 '<h2>Why Andaman for Diving?</h2><p>The Andaman Sea is one of the world''s richest marine ecosystems, with over 500 species of fish, 200 species of coral, sea turtles, manta rays, and occasional whale sharks. Underwater visibility ranges from 15-30 meters (exceptional for Indian waters).</p><h2>Best Dive Sites</h2><p><strong>Havelock Island (Radhanagar & Elephant Beach):</strong> Perfect for beginners. Shallow, calm water with vibrant corals and colorful reef fish. Visibility 10-20m.</p><p><strong>Neil Island:</strong> Great reef walls. Regular turtle sightings. Less crowded than Havelock.</p><p><strong>Barren Island:</strong> Advanced divers only. India''s only active volcano rises from the sea. Dramatic black sand seafloor, hammerhead sharks, and manta rays. One of Asia''s most unique dive sites.</p><p><strong>North Bay & Jolly Buoy:</strong> Perfect for snorkelers and first-time divers. Shallow, protected, and incredibly colorful.</p><h2>PADI Courses</h2><p>Several PADI-certified dive centers operate in Havelock. An introductory Discover Scuba Diving course costs Rs. 3,500-5,000. The Open Water Diver certification (3 days) costs Rs. 18,000-25,000. Book in advance during peak season.</p><h2>Best Time to Dive</h2><p>November to April is best for diving — calm seas, high visibility (20-30m). May-October is monsoon with rough seas and reduced visibility. Barren Island dives run October-May only.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1450363/pexels-photo-1450363.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Adventure', ARRAY['Andaman','Scuba Diving','Water Sports','Beach','Havelock'], 'Maya Krishnan', 9, true, '2025-04-20 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013009-0000-4000-8000-000000000009', 'golden-temple-amritsar-guide', 'Golden Temple Amritsar: A Complete Guide to India''s Most Visited Shrine',
 'The Harmandir Sahib (Golden Temple) in Amritsar is India''s most visited shrine — welcoming over 100,000 pilgrims and visitors daily. This guide covers the history, significance, best time to visit, langar experience, and things to do in Amritsar.',
 '<h2>The Harmandir Sahib</h2><p>The Golden Temple is the holiest Gurdwara in Sikhism, built in 1589 by the 5th Sikh Guru, Guru Arjan Dev Ji. The temple''s upper floors are covered with 750kg of gold leaf donated by Maharaja Ranjit Singh in the early 19th century. The temple sits in the middle of the Amrit Sarovar (sacred pool of nectar) from which Amritsar derives its name.</p><h2>The Langar — Community Kitchen</h2><p>The Golden Temple''s langar is the world''s largest free kitchen, serving 50,000-100,000 people daily with simple vegetarian meals prepared and served by volunteers (sewadars). Participating in the langar — either eating or volunteering to help cook/serve — is one of the most humbling and moving experiences you can have in India. It is open 24 hours and free for everyone regardless of religion, caste, or nationality.</p><h2>Amrit Vela (The Golden Hour)</h2><p>The most spiritually powerful time to visit is Amrit Vela — the ambrosial hour before dawn (3:30-4:00 AM). The temple is far less crowded, the gold reflects dramatically in the dark pool, and the Gurbani (sacred hymns) echo through the misty morning air. This is when the Guru Granth Sahib (the eternal living Guru) is ceremonially brought to the temple.</p><h2>Wagah Border</h2><p>28km from Amritsar on the India-Pakistan border, the Wagah Ceremony happens every evening at sunset. Indian and Pakistani soldiers perform an elaborate flag-lowering ceremony with high kicks, synchronized marching, and nationalistic fervor. Crowds on both sides cheer. An unmissable, goosebump-inducing spectacle.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/3571111/pexels-photo-3571111.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Pilgrimage', ARRAY['Amritsar','Golden Temple','Sikhism','Wagah Border','Punjab'], 'Gurpreet Kaur', 10, true, '2025-05-01 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013010-0000-4000-8000-000000000010', 'dubai-travel-tips-indians', 'Dubai Travel Guide for Indians: Visa, Budget, and Best Experiences 2025',
 'Dubai is one of the most visited destinations for Indian travelers. This guide covers everything from the UAE visa process, currency exchange tips, best malls vs. old souks, halal food scene, and how to experience Dubai beyond the standard tourist trail.',
 '<h2>UAE Visa for Indians</h2><p>Indian passport holders require a UAE visa. Options: (1) Visa on Arrival for holders of valid USA/UK/EU/Schengen visa — 14 days, free; (2) Tourist Visa through airline (Emirates, Air India, etc.) — 30/60/90 days; (3) eVisa through ICA portal. Cost ranges from AED 250-500 depending on duration. Processing takes 3-5 business days. Always apply at least 2 weeks in advance during peak season (Dec-Jan).</p><h2>Currency Tips</h2><p>1 AED ≈ Rs. 22-23. Dubai is expensive — a mid-range restaurant meal costs AED 50-100 (Rs. 1,100-2,200). Exchange currency at airport forex counters (rates are decent) or use UAE dirhams from your Indian bank before departure. Avoid exchanging at hotels — rates are poor. Credit cards are widely accepted but carry AED 500-1000 in cash for souks and taxis.</p><h2>Burj Khalifa: Plan Ahead</h2><p>The world''s tallest building (828m) is Dubai''s must-do. At The Top (124th & 125th floor): AED 149 in advance, AED 250+ at the counter. At The Top Sky (148th floor + lounge): AED 369+. Buy tickets online 2-3 days in advance — same-day tickets are expensive and limited. Evening slots (sunset/night) are more atmospheric but pricier.</p><h2>Hidden Dubai</h2><p>Beyond the mega malls and artificial islands, Dubai has a fascinating old soul: Al Fahidi Historical Neighbourhood (wind-tower architecture, the best coffee shops, art galleries), the Gold Souk (Deira, 10,000+ kg of gold on display), Spice Souk (saffron, frankincense, dried limes), and the traditional dhow wharfage along the Creek where century-old wooden boats still transport goods to Iran and Somalia.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2044434/pexels-photo-2044434.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Destination Guide', ARRAY['Dubai','UAE','International Travel','Travel Tips','Burj Khalifa'], 'Sharmila Patel', 11, true, '2025-05-15 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013011-0000-4000-8000-000000000011', 'navagraha-temples-kumbakonam-guide', 'Navagraha Temples of Tamil Nadu: The Complete Pilgrimage Guide',
 'The nine Navagraha temples around Kumbakonam are believed to appease the nine planetary deities and nullify astrological doshas. This guide covers all nine temples, the best order to visit them, astrological significance, and practical travel tips.',
 '<h2>The Nine Planets</h2><p>In Hindu astrology, the nine celestial bodies (Navagrahas) — Surya (Sun), Chandra (Moon), Mangala/Angaraka (Mars), Budha (Mercury), Guru (Jupiter), Shukra (Venus), Shani (Saturn), Rahu (North Node), and Ketu (South Node) — each have dedicated temples in Tamil Nadu. A complete circuit is believed to grant relief from astrological afflictions and bring planetary harmony.</p><h2>The Nine Temples</h2><p><strong>Suryanar Kovil (Surya/Sun):</strong> Situated at Suryanar Kovil village near Kumbakonam. The most important of the Navagraha temples. Sun god presides at the center.</p><p><strong>Thingaloor (Chandra/Moon):</strong> 17km from Kumbakonam. Lord Kailasanathar temple. Mondays are most auspicious.</p><p><strong>Vaideeswaran Kovil (Angaraka/Mars):</strong> Also called the Divine Physician — prayers here are believed to cure diseases.</p><p><strong>Thiruvengadu (Budha/Mercury):</strong> 70km from Kumbakonam. Swetaranyeswara and Brahmavidya Ambika preside. Wednesdays are auspicious.</p><p><strong>Alangudi (Guru/Jupiter):</strong> 20km from Kumbakonam. Lord Apatsahayeswarar. Thursdays are most powerful.</p><p><strong>Kanjanur (Shukra/Venus):</strong> 25km from Kumbakonam. Agneeswarar Temple. Fridays for best results.</p><p><strong>Thirunallar (Shani/Saturn):</strong> 85km from Kumbakonam near Karaikal. Lord Dharbaranyeswarar and Shaneeswara. Saturdays draw enormous crowds — thousands come for Shani puja.</p><p><strong>Keezhaperumpallam (Rahu):</strong> Near Poompuhar. A joint temple for Rahu and Ketu.</p><p><strong>Keezhperumpallam (Ketu):</strong> Same temple complex — Rahu and Ketu face opposite directions.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1603650/pexels-photo-1603650.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Pilgrimage', ARRAY['Navagraha','Kumbakonam','Tamil Nadu','Astrology','Temple Tour'], 'Subramaniam Pillai', 14, true, '2025-06-01 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013012-0000-4000-8000-000000000012', 'maldives-vs-andaman-comparison', 'Maldives vs Andaman: Which Should You Choose for Your Island Holiday?',
 'Two of Asia''s most beautiful island destinations — the Maldives and the Andaman Islands. Both offer turquoise waters, white sand beaches, and world-class snorkeling. But they are very different experiences at very different price points. Here''s how to decide.',
 '<h2>The Key Difference</h2><p>Maldives is about seclusion, luxury, and over-the-ocean living. Andaman is about adventure, nature, history, and accessible beauty. Maldives is for your honeymoon; Andaman is for your next adventure trip.</p><h2>Budget Comparison</h2><p><strong>Maldives:</strong> Budget traveler: Rs. 50,000-70,000 per person (5 days). Mid-range: Rs. 80,000-1,20,000 per person. Luxury (overwater villa): Rs. 2,00,000+ per person. Guesthouse islands (Maafushi, Thoddoo) are the budget option.</p><p><strong>Andaman:</strong> Budget: Rs. 15,000-20,000 per person (5 days). Mid-range: Rs. 25,000-40,000 per person. Includes airfare from Chennai/Kolkata, accommodation, and most activities.</p><h2>Marine Life</h2><p>Both have excellent marine life. Andaman has better fish diversity and reef health in many areas. Maldives wins for megafauna — manta rays, whale sharks, and hammerheads are more reliably seen. Maldives has vastly more dive sites, including famous drift dives and night dives.</p><h2>Beach Quality</h2><p>Maldives wins on beach quality — powdery white sand, crystal clear turquoise water, zero seaweed. The lagoons are shallow, calm, and impossibly photogenic. Andaman''s Radhanagar Beach (Havelock) is widely considered one of Asia''s best beaches and rivals many Maldives beaches in beauty.</p><h2>Our Recommendation</h2><p>For honeymooners with a budget above Rs. 1 lakh per person: Maldives. For adventure travelers, families, or those seeking value without compromising beauty: Andaman. If budget is between Rs. 40,000-80,000, Andaman gives significantly better value.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1450363/pexels-photo-1450363.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Destination Guide', ARRAY['Maldives','Andaman','Comparison','Island Holiday','Honeymoon'], 'Priya Sharma', 8, true, '2025-06-10 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013013-0000-4000-8000-000000000013', 'goa-offseason-travel-guide', 'Goa in Monsoon: Why the Off-Season Might Be the Best Time to Visit',
 'Most tourists visit Goa in winter (Nov-Feb), but the off-season monsoon months (June-September) offer a completely different, arguably more beautiful, Goa — lush green jungles, thundering waterfalls, empty beaches, and 40% lower prices.',
 '<h2>Why Monsoon Goa is Special</h2><p>Goa transforms in the monsoon. The brown, dry landscape explodes into fifty shades of green. Hidden waterfalls (Dudhsagar, Tambdi Surla, Cola Beach) reach their full, thunderous glory. The beaches, emptied of tourists, become wild and windswept — dramatic rather than beautiful. And hotel rates drop by 30-50%.</p><h2>What''s Open, What''s Not</h2><p><strong>Open:</strong> Most restaurants and cafes, inland attractions (Dudhsagar waterfall, Spice farms, Old Goa churches), heritage walks, Panjim market, casinos, nightclubs.</p><p><strong>Closed:</strong> Many beach shacks, water sports operators, most North Goa beach clubs (especially June-July). Swimming is NOT safe during monsoon — powerful currents and rip tides.</p><h2>Monsoon Highlights</h2><p><strong>Dudhsagar Falls:</strong> Only accessible during and just after monsoon — the milk-white cascade plunging 310m through the jungle is absolutely spectacular. Best visited August-October.</p><p><strong>Jeep Safari through Wildlife Sanctuary:</strong> Bhagwan Mahavir Wildlife Sanctuary and Cotigao Wildlife Sanctuary are best explored in the green season when wildlife is most active.</p><p><strong>Fontainhas Heritage Walk:</strong> Panjim''s Latin Quarter, with its Portuguese-tiled houses and narrow lanes, is best enjoyed in the gentle monsoon drizzle.</p><h2>Practical Tips</h2><p>Carry waterproof sandals or shoes, a good rain jacket (umbrella is useless in Goa''s horizontal rain), and a waterproof bag. Mold and dampness are issues — air your clothes daily. Rent a scooter rather than cycling — roads are slippery but manageable with care.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1007657/pexels-photo-1007657.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Travel Guide', ARRAY['Goa','Monsoon Travel','Off-Season','Dudhsagar','Budget Travel'], 'Rohan D''Souza', 9, true, '2025-06-20 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013014-0000-4000-8000-000000000014', 'manali-snow-activities-guide', 'Manali Winter & Snow Activities: The Complete Adventure Guide',
 'Manali in winter (December to February) is a snow-lover''s paradise. This guide covers the best snow activities — skiing at Solang, snowshoeing, snowmobiling, and the spectacular Rohtang Pass snowfields — along with safety tips and accommodation.',
 '<h2>Solang Valley — Activity Hub</h2><p>Solang Valley, 14km from Manali, is the main activity hub for winter sports. Activities available: skiing, snowboarding, snow scooter, zorbing (rolling down in a ball), and snow jeep rides. Best months: December to February when snow depth is 1-2 meters.</p><h2>Skiing in Manali</h2><p>Solang Valley has basic ski slopes — good for beginners, limited for intermediate/advanced. More serious skiers should consider Kullu-Manali Ski School at Rohtang (when open) or the more developed ski resort at Auli (Uttarakhand) which has a 3km slope and chairlift. Rental equipment (skis, boots, poles) at Solang costs Rs. 400-600/hour.</p><h2>Rohtang Pass</h2><p>At 3978m, Rohtang Pass is the gateway to Lahaul and Spiti. In winter, only the approach (up to Rohtang barrier) is accessible — but this section has excellent snow and dramatic mountain views. Requires a permit (Rs. 550, available online at rohtangpermits.nic.in) and is closed on Tuesdays for ecological maintenance. Snow depth here reaches 3-5 meters in peak winter.</p><h2>Atal Tunnel & Sissu</h2><p>The Atal Tunnel (9.2km, world''s longest mountain tunnel at 10,000ft) now provides year-round access to the Lahaul Valley. Sissu on the other side is a winter wonderland with frozen lakes and pristine Himalayan villages — accessible even in peak winter.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2387871/pexels-photo-2387871.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Adventure', ARRAY['Manali','Snow Activities','Skiing','Winter Travel','Himachal Pradesh'], 'Arjun Thakur', 10, true, '2025-07-01 09:00:00+05:30'),

('bb013015-0000-4000-8000-000000000015', 'hampi-heritage-karnataka-guide', 'Hampi: The Forgotten Capital of the Vijayanagara Empire',
 'Hampi is one of India''s most extraordinary UNESCO World Heritage Sites — a landscape of massive boulders strewn with 500-year-old ruins of what was once the world''s second-largest medieval city. This guide helps you discover its magic.',
 '<h2>Brief History</h2><p>Hampi was the capital of the Vijayanagara Empire (1336-1646 CE), which at its peak was the wealthiest city in the world after Beijing. The empire was sacked by the Deccan Sultanates in 1565 at the Battle of Talikota, and the city was burned and looted for months. What remains today are the stone structures — hundreds of temples, market streets, elephant stables, and water systems spread over 4,190 hectares.</p><h2>Must-See Sites</h2><p><strong>Virupaksha Temple:</strong> Still an active place of worship, this is Hampi''s most iconic landmark. The 50-meter gopuram (tower) dominates the landscape.</p><p><strong>Vittala Temple:</strong> The architectural masterpiece of Hampi. The stone chariot (which appears on the Indian 50-rupee note), the musical pillars that produce different notes when struck, and the Kalyana Mandapa are extraordinary.</p><p><strong>Matanga Hill:</strong> For the best panoramic view of Hampi''s boulder landscape, climb Matanga Hill at sunrise or sunset. The view of the Tungabhadra River weaving through the boulders is unforgettable.</p><p><strong>Lotus Mahal & Elephant Stables:</strong> The royal enclosure''s ornate Lotus Mahal (believed to be a royal women''s pavilion) and the vaulted Elephant Stables (housing 11 elephants) showcase the empire''s Indo-Saracenic architecture.</p><h2>Practical Tips</h2><p>Hampi is a 3-4 hour drive from Bengaluru or a 9-hour overnight train to Hospet junction. Best explored on bicycle or motorized scooter. April-November is hot; December-February is ideal. Minimum 2 full days needed; 3-4 days for the complete experience.</p>',
 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/3573351/pexels-photo-3573351.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
 'Destination Guide', ARRAY['Hampi','Karnataka','UNESCO','Heritage','Vijayanagara'], 'Dr. Padmini Rao', 12, true, '2025-07-15 09:00:00+05:30')

